          "body": "Read as a whole, Mark 7 is the Gospel's most systematic argument for Gentile inclusion *from Jesus' own ministry*. The logic: (1) the food laws and ritual washings were the chief sociological wall between Jew and Gentile; (2) Jesus abolishes them on His own authority by relocating defilement to the heart; (3) therefore He proceeds into Gentile territory; (4) where He demonstrates Gentile faith (Syrophoenician) and fulfills messianic Gentile-age prophecy (the deaf man in Decapolis). Paul will later argue the same case in Galatians 2 and Ephesians 2:14-16, and Peter will receive its vision in Acts 10. But Mark's claim is that the doctrine and the practice are Jesus' own — not an apostolic innovation, but the Messiah's manifest intent from the middle of His Galilean ministry."
